{"actual_usd":0.1243,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":192,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24284,"reply":"\"No... I don't think that quite holds.\" *I rub a bit of dried clay off my thumb with my forefinger, watching it flake onto the table between us.* \"The cross isn't just the bad part Christ had to endure so the 'real' thing could happen later. The cross is where He actually gave Himself—where sin was dealt with, where the cost was borne. The resurrection matters just as much, mind you, but differently. It's the Father's vindication of the Son, death broken open, the proof that what happened on the cross truly held.\"\n\n*I lean back a touch, the bench giving a soft creak.* \"If you split them too hard, you lose the shape of the thing. No cross, and resurrection turns into a miracle without atonement. No resurrection, and the cross can start to look like tragedy without victory. Scripture keeps them married close. What's making you ask it that way?\"","rolling_24h_usd":50.702010000000044,"run_id":"eb655daa-b6c7-404d-bc0e-a582b45ff8c6"}
